//     both stable and unstable sorting. This is handled via the `UNSTABLE`
//     preprocessor macro. Using `std::bool_constant` allows the compiler to
//     specialize the code path at compile time, ensuring zero overhead for this
//     choice. Unstable sorting can be slightly faster as it offers more
//     flexibility to the permutation algorithm.
//
// 5.  **Robust Bit Calculation**: When the number of bits is not specified by
//     the user, it is determined by finding the maximum key in the input. This
//     is performed efficiently with a single parallel reduction (`parlay::reduce`).
//     This makes the sort adaptive to the actual data range, which can save
//     unnecessary work if the keys are small. Edge cases (empty input, all-zero
