An expert implementation of a parallel histogram must be robust against various data distributions. A naive approach using atomic increments on a shared histogram array suffers from severe performance degradation under high contention, which occurs when many threads try to update the same few buckets simultaneously (e.g., with exponential or almost-equal distributions).

The fastest and most scalable approach for a general-purpose, shared-memory parallel histogram is a two-phase method using thread-local storage.

1.  **Phase 1: Local Counting.** The input data is partitioned among the available worker threads. Each thread computes a histogram for its local partition into a private array. Since each thread is the sole writer to its private histogram, this phase is completely free of locks, atomics, and contention, allowing it to run at nearly ideal parallel speed.

2.  **Phase 2: Parallel Reduction.** After all threads have completed their local histograms, the results must be combined. This is done by performing a parallel reduction. The task of summing the counts for each bucket is parallelized, where each output bucket is computed by summing the corresponding entries from all the private histograms.

This method trades increased memory usage (one private histogram per thread) for a massive gain in performance and scalability by eliminating synchronization bottlenecks in the main counting loop. The following implementation robustly applies this state-of-the-art technique using ParlayLib.

#start
```cpp
#include "parlay/primitives.h"
#include "parlay/sequence.h"
#include "parlay/parallel.h"
#include <algorithm>

// This implementation uses a classic two-phase approach for parallel histogramming
// to achieve high performance and avoid contention, which is crucial for skewed
// data distributions.
//
// Phase 1: Local Histogram Calculation
// - The input sequence is partitioned among the available worker threads.
// - Each worker thread computes a histogram for its assigned partition of the data
//   into a private, thread-local buffer.
// - Since each thread writes only to its own private histogram, there are no
//   race conditions or atomic operations required in this phase. This allows
//   the counting loop to run at maximum speed, free from synchronization overhead
//   and false sharing.
//
// Phase 2: Parallel Reduction
// - After all local histograms are computed, they are combined (reduced) into
//   the final global histogram.
// - This reduction is also done in parallel. The task of summing the counts for
//   each bucket is parallelized across the buckets. For each bucket `i`, one
//   thread sums `local_hists[0][i] + local_hists[1][i] + ...`.
//
// This strategy trades increased memory usage (for the local histograms) for
// a significant reduction in contention, making it one of the fastest and most
// scalable methods for parallel histogram construction on shared-memory systems.

parlay::sequence<uint> histogram(parlay::sequence<uint> const &In, uint buckets) {
  // Handle empty input as a base case.
  if (In.empty()) {
    return parlay::sequence<uint>(buckets, 0);
  }

  // Determine the number of worker threads to use.
  size_t num_workers = parlay::num_workers();

  // --- Phase 1: Local Histogram Calculation ---

  // Create a 2D sequence to store the private histogram for each worker.
  // Using size_t for counts prevents potential overflow on large inputs before
  // casting to the required uint for the final result.
  parlay::sequence<parlay::sequence<size_t>> local_hists(num_workers);
  for (size_t i = 0; i < num_workers; ++i) {
    // Each worker gets its own histogram, initialized to zeros.
    local_hists[i] = parlay::sequence<size_t>(buckets, 0);
  }

  // Parallel loop over the workers. Each worker processes a block of the input.
  parlay::parallel_for(0, num_workers, [&](size_t worker_id) {
    // Calculate the range of the input sequence for this worker.
    // This partitioning ensures that the entire input is covered and is robust
    // to input sizes that are not divisible by the number of workers.
    size_t block_size = (In.size() + num_workers - 1) / num_workers;
    size_t start = std::min(worker_id * block_size, In.size());
    size_t end = std::min(start + block_size, In.size());

    // Get a reference to this worker's private histogram.
    auto& my_hist = local_hists[worker_id];

    // Iterate over the assigned sub-sequence and update the private histogram.
    // This is the core counting loop and is free of any synchronization.
    for (size_t i = start; i < end; ++i) {
      // Input values are guaranteed to be in the range [0, buckets).
      // No bounds checking is necessary for performance.
      my_hist[In[i]]++;
    }
  });

  // --- Phase 2: Parallel Reduction ---

  // Create the final result sequence.
  auto result = parlay::sequence<uint>(buckets);

  // Parallelize the reduction step over the buckets.
  // This is highly effective when `buckets` is large.
  parlay::parallel_for(0, buckets, [&](size_t i) {
    // For each bucket `i`, sum the counts from all worker-local histograms.
    size_t total = 0;
    for (size_t j = 0; j < num_workers; ++j) {
      total += local_hists[j][i];
    }
    // Store the final count, casting back to the required output type.
    result[i] = static_cast<uint>(total);
  });

  return result;
}
