An expert C++ programmer would recognize that a direct parallelization of the provided serial Kruskal's algorithm is difficult due to the sequential dependencies in the union-find loop. The fastest parallel MSF algorithms are typically hybrids, often based on Boruvka's algorithm, which is naturally parallel.

The following implementation uses a parallel version of Boruvka's algorithm. This algorithm works in rounds. In each round, it finds the minimum-weight edge leaving each component of the spanning forest and adds these edges to the MSF. This process exponentially reduces the number of active components, leading to a logarithmic number of rounds.

### Key Features of the Implementation:

1.  **High-Level Parallelism**: The algorithm is parallel at a high level, structured into rounds. Each round consists of several parallel steps.
2.  **Parallel Edge Finding**: In each round, the minimum outgoing edge for every component is found in parallel using atomic `write_min` operations. This avoids race conditions while ensuring each component's best edge is recorded.
3.  **Deterministic Tie-Breaking**: When multiple edges have the same minimum weight, ties are broken using the original edge index, ensuring deterministic results.
4.  **Efficient Component Merging**: Requests to merge components are generated in parallel, then made unique to ensure only one edge is added between any pair of components per round. The union operations themselves are performed in a short sequential loop, which is efficient because the number of components (and thus merge requests) decreases exponentially.
5.  **Parallel Edge Filtering**: After each round of merging, edges that now connect vertices within the same component are removed in parallel. This significantly reduces the amount of work for subsequent rounds, which is crucial for performance, especially on sparse graphs.
6.  **Leveraging ParlayLib**: The implementation makes extensive use of ParlayLib's high-performance parallel primitives like `parallel_for`, `tabulate`, `map_filter`, `sort`, and `filter`.

This Boruvka-based approach is fundamentally more parallel than Kruskal's algorithm and is a standard choice for high-performance parallel MSF computation.

#start
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <algorithm>
#include <atomic>
#include <vector>
#include <optional>

#include "parlay/parallel.h"
#include "parlay/primitives.h"
#include "parlay/sequence.h"
#include "parlay/sort.h"

#include "common/graph.h"
#include "common/get_time.h"
#include "common/atomics.h"
#include "algorithm/union_find.h"
#include "MST.h"

// **************************************************************
//    PARALLEL MSF USING BORUVKA'S ALGORITHM
// **************************************************************

// An edge with its original index
struct Edge {
  vertexId u;
  vertexId v;
  edgeWeight weight;
  edgeId id;
};

// Represents the best edge found so far for a component
struct BestEdge {
  edgeWeight weight;
  edgeId id;
};

// Comparator for BestEdge, used for atomic write_min.
// Breaks ties deterministically using edge ID.
auto best_edge_less = [](const BestEdge& a, const BestEdge& b) {
  if (a.weight != b.weight) return a.weight < b.weight;
  return a.id < b.id;
};

// Represents a request to union two components, created by the component with the smaller ID.
struct UnionRequest {
  vertexId u; // smaller component root ID
  vertexId v; // larger component root ID
  edgeId id;

  // For sorting and uniqueness
  bool operator<(const UnionRequest& other) const {
    if (u != other.u) return u < other.u;
    if (v != other.v) return v < other.v;
    return id < other.id;
  }
};

// Comparator for checking equality of the component-pair part of a request
auto union_request_equal = [](const UnionRequest& a, const UnionRequest& b) {
    return a.u == b.u && a.v == b.v;
};


parlay::sequence<edgeId> mst(wghEdgeArray<vertexId, edgeWeight> &G) {
  size_t n = G.n;
  size_t m = G.m;

  if (m == 0) {
    return parlay::sequence<edgeId>();
  }

  // 1. Create a sequence of edges with their original IDs for processing
  auto all_edges = parlay::tabulate(m, [&](size_t i) -> Edge {
    return {G.E[i].u, G.E[i].v, G.E[i].weight, static_cast<edgeId>(i)};
  });

  unionFind<vertexId> uf(n);
  parlay::sequence<edgeId> mst_edges;
  mst_edges.reserve(n > 0 ? n - 1 : 0);

  size_t num_components = n;

  parlay::sequence<Edge> active_edges = all_edges;

  // Boruvka's algorithm loop
  while (num_components > 1 && !active_edges.empty()) {

    // 2. Find the minimum weight edge for each component in parallel
    parlay::sequence<BestEdge> min_edges(n, {std::numeric_limits<edgeWeight>::max(), static_cast<edgeId>(-1)});

    parlay::parallel_for(0, active_edges.size(), [&](size_t i) {
      const auto& edge = active_edges[i];
      vertexId root_u = uf.find(edge.u);
      vertexId root_v = uf.find(edge.v);
      if (root_u != root_v) {
        BestEdge be = {edge.weight, edge.id};
        pbbs::write_min(&min_edges[root_u], be, best_edge_less);
        pbbs::write_min(&min_edges[root_v], be, best_edge_less);
      }
    });

    // 3. Identify union requests from the best edges found for each component
    auto requests = parlay::map_filter(parlay::iota<vertexId>(n), [&](vertexId i) {
      if (uf.is_root(i) && min_edges[i].id != static_cast<edgeId>(-1)) {
        const auto& edge = all_edges[min_edges[i].id];
        vertexId root_u = uf.find(edge.u);
        vertexId root_v = uf.find(edge.v);
        vertexId other_root = (root_u == i) ? root_v : root_u;

        // To avoid duplicate requests, only the smaller root ID makes a request to the larger one.
        if (i < other_root) {
          return std::optional<UnionRequest>({i, other_root, min_edges[i].id});
        }
      }
      return std::optional<UnionRequest>();
    });

    if (requests.empty()) {
      break; // No more edges can be added; graph may be disconnected.
    }

    // 4. Sort requests to group requests for the same component pair together.
    // The sort is stable and uses edge ID as a tie-breaker, ensuring determinism.
    parlay::sort_inplace(requests);

    // 5. Select one edge for each unique component pair to be merged.
    // `unique` keeps the first item in each group of equal items. Due to the sort order,
    // this will be the edge with the minimum original ID.
    auto unique_requests = parlay::unique(requests, union_request_equal);

    // 6. Add selected edges to MST and perform unions.
    // This part is sequential but fast, as the number of unique requests decreases exponentially.
    size_t components_before_union = num_components;
    for (const auto& req : unique_requests) {
      vertexId root_u = uf.find(req.u);
      vertexId root_v = uf.find(req.v);
      if (root_u != root_v) {
        uf.union_roots(root_u, root_v);
        mst_edges.push_back(req.id);
        num_components--;
      }
    }

    if (num_components == components_before_union) {
        break; // No progress made, remaining components are disconnected.
    }

    // 7. In parallel, filter out edges that are now internal to a component for the next round.
    if (num_components > 1) {
        active_edges = parlay::filter(active_edges, [&](const Edge& edge) {
            return uf.find(edge.u) != uf.find(edge.v);
        });
    }
  }

  return mst_edges;
}
```
