An expert C++ programmer would recognize that a simple greedy algorithm for maximal matching is inherently sequential due to data dependencies. A direct parallelization using locks or fine-grained atomics can be complex and prone to contention or correctness issues like deadlocks and race conditions.

The most effective way to parallelize this type of greedy algorithm, especially within the ParlayLib ecosystem, is to use a framework designed for such dependencies, like `speculative_for`. This approach attempts to process many edges in parallel and only retries the ones that conflict.

Here is the high-performance parallel implementation of Maximal Matching using this strategy:

### Algorithm Description

This implementation uses a parallel greedy approach based on speculative execution. The core idea is to process all edges in parallel and use a reservation system to handle conflicts where multiple edges attempt to match the same vertex.

1.  **Speculative Execution**: We use `pbbs::speculative_for` to iterate over all edges. This framework allows iterations to fail and be retried if they conflict with others. An "iteration" `i` corresponds to considering the `i`-th edge in the input array.

2.  **Reservation System**: A `pbbs::reservation` object is associated with each vertex. When processing an edge `i = (u, v)`, it tries to "reserve" its endpoints `u` and `v` by writing its own index `i` into their reservation slots. The underlying `write_min` operation ensures that if multiple edges contend for the same vertex, the edge with the smallest index wins the reservation. This provides a deterministic and efficient greedy tie-breaking rule.

3.  **Commit Phase**: After the reservation attempts, each edge checks if it successfully won the reservation for both of its endpoints.
    *   If an edge won both reservations, it is added to the matching. Its endpoints are then permanently marked as "matched" using a separate atomic flag array. This completes a successful "commit".
    *   If an edge lost either reservation, its commit fails, and `speculative_for` will automatically retry processing this edge in a later round.

4.  **State Propagation**: The atomic `matched_v` array ensures that once a vertex is part of a committed match, no other edges incident to it will be considered in subsequent speculative rounds. The `reserve` step checks this array and immediately aborts the processing for an edge (without scheduling a retry) if either of its endpoints is already matched, effectively pruning the set of active edges.

This approach avoids explicit locking, minimizes contention, and scales well by processing a large number of non-conflicting edges in parallel in each round of speculation.

```cpp
#start
#include <iostream>
#include "parlay/parallel.h"
#include "parlay/primitives.h"
#include "common/graph.h"
#include "common/speculative_for.h"
#include "common/get_time.h"
#include "matching.h"

#include <atomic>

parlay::sequence<edgeId> maximalMatching(edges const &E) {
  size_t n = std::max(E.numCols, E.numRows);
  size_t m = E.nonZeros;

  if (m == 0) {
    return parlay::sequence<edgeId>();
  }

  // Reservation for each vertex to resolve conflicts within a speculative_for batch.
  // An edge `i` tries to reserve its endpoints by writing `i` into the slot.
  // The edge with the smallest index wins due to write_min.
  parlay::sequence<pbbs::reservation<size_t>> R(n);

  // Marks vertices that are part of a committed match.
  // This state is carried across speculative_for batches.
  // `std::atomic<bool>` ensures visibility between threads and rounds.
  parlay::sequence<std::atomic<bool>> matched_v(n);
  parlay::parallel_for(0, n, [&](size_t i) {
    matched_v[i].store(false, std::memory_order_relaxed);
  });

  // Output flag for each edge. True if the edge is in the matching.
  parlay::sequence<bool> in_matching(m, false);

  // The state and logic for a single step of the speculative execution.
  struct MMState {
    const edges& E;
    parlay::sequence<pbbs::reservation<size_t>>& R;
    parlay::sequence<std::atomic<bool>>& matched_v;
    parlay::sequence<bool>& in_matching;

    MMState(const edges& _E,
            parlay::sequence<pbbs::reservation<size_t>>& _R,
            parlay::sequence<std::atomic<bool>>& _matched_v,
            parlay::sequence<bool>& _in_matching)
        : E(_E), R(_R), matched_v(_matched_v), in_matching(_in_matching) {}

    // The reserve phase. Called for a batch of speculative iterations.
    // An iteration `i` corresponds to considering edge `E[i]`.
    bool reserve(size_t i) {
      auto u = E[i].u;
      auto v = E[i].v;

      // If either endpoint is already part of a committed match from a
      // previous batch, this edge is obsolete. Return false to
      // signal to speculative_for that this iteration should not be retried.
      if (matched_v[u].load(std::memory_order_acquire) ||
          matched_v[v].load(std::memory_order_acquire)) {
        return false;
      }

      // Try to reserve both endpoints. The one with the lower edge index wins.
      R[u].reserve(i);
      R[v].reserve(i);
      return true;
    }

    // The commit phase. Called for iterations that were reserved.
    // Returns true on success (iteration is finished).
    // Returns false on failure (iteration should be retried).
    bool commit(size_t i) {
      auto u = E[i].u;
      auto v = E[i].v;

      // Check if we won the reservation for both endpoints.
      // The check is against our own edge index `i`.
      if (R[u].check(i) && R[v].check(i)) {
        // Success! We won the race for this batch.
        // Mark the edge as part of the matching.
        in_matching[i] = true;

        // Mark vertices as matched to prevent any other edges
        // from matching with them in future batches. This store must be
        // visible to other threads in their `reserve` phase.
        matched_v[u].store(true, std::memory_order_release);
        matched_v[v].store(true, std::memory_order_release);
        return true;
      }

      // We lost the reservation on at least one endpoint to another edge
      // with a smaller index in the same batch. Fail and let
      // speculative_for retry this iteration.
      return false;
    }
  };

  MMState state(E, R, matched_v, in_matching);

  // Run the speculative loop over all edges.
  // Granularity is a tuning parameter. A small value like 20 is a
  // reasonable starting point. It controls the size of the batches
  // processed by speculative_for.
  pbbs::speculative_for(state, (size_t)0, m, 20);

  // Collect the indices of the edges that were added to the matching.
  auto edge_indices = parlay::iota<edgeId>(m);
  return parlay::pack(edge_indices, in_matching);
}
#end

An expert C++ programmer would recognize that the simple serial greedy algorithm for maximal matching has a loop-carried dependency that prevents trivial parallelization. The key challenge is handling conflicts where multiple parallel threads attempt to match edges that share a vertex.

A highly effective and efficient parallel approach is to use a reservation-based system, which can be implemented cleanly with speculative execution. The provided `pbbs::speculative_for` is an ideal tool for this. The core idea is to process edges in parallel batches. For each edge, a thread attempts to "reserve" its two endpoint vertices. Conflicts are resolved based on priority—in this case, the edge's original index in the input array. The edge with the lower index wins, which makes the parallel algorithm deterministic and ensures it produces the same result as the serial greedy algorithm.

This implementation encapsulates the logic for reserving and committing a match into a `MatchingStep` struct. It uses an array of `std::atomic<vertexId>` to manage reservations for each vertex. The `speculative_for` engine handles the details of batching, retrying failed attempts, and ensuring that all edges are eventually processed. Finally, a parallel filter collects the indices of the edges that successfully won their reservations, forming the maximal matching. This approach minimizes explicit locking, scales well, and is significantly faster than the serial baseline.

Here is the implementation:
#start
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <atomic>
#include <limits>
#include "parlay/parallel.h"
#include "parlay/primitives.h"
#include "common/graph.h"
#include "common/speculative_for.h"
#include "matching.h"

// The MatchingStep struct defines the logic for a single step within the
// speculative_for loop. It attempts to match a single edge.
// This implementation ensures that when there is a conflict between two edges
// for a vertex, the edge with the smaller index in the input array wins.
// This makes the parallel algorithm deterministic and produce the same result
// as the simple serial greedy algorithm.
struct MatchingStep {
    using vertexId = uint;
    using edgeId = uint;

    const edgeArray<vertexId>& E;
    parlay::sequence<std::atomic<vertexId>>& reservations;
    static constexpr vertexId UNMATCHED = std::numeric_limits<vertexId>::max();

    MatchingStep(const edgeArray<vertexId>& _E, parlay::sequence<std::atomic<vertexId>>& _R)
        : E(_E), reservations(_R) {}

    // The reserve phase of the speculative execution.
    // It attempts to reserve the two endpoints of an edge.
    // Returns false if the edge is guaranteed to fail (i.e., one of its
    // endpoints is already taken by a lower-ID edge), true otherwise to
    // proceed to the commit phase.
    bool reserve(edgeId i) {
        vertexId u = E[i].u;
        vertexId v = E[i].v;

        // Optimization: if either endpoint is already matched by a lower-ID edge,
        // this edge can never be in the matching. We can abort early.
        // A relaxed load is sufficient as this is just a speculative check.
        if (reservations[u].load(std::memory_order_relaxed) < i || 
            reservations[v].load(std::memory_order_relaxed) < i) {
            return false;
        }

        // Try to reserve u and v by being the new minimum edge ID.
        // The edge with the smaller index wins any race.
        parlay::write_min(&reservations[u], i, std::less<vertexId>());
        parlay::write_min(&reservations[v], i, std::less<vertexId>());

        // Proceed to the commit phase to check if we won the reservations.
        return true;
    }

    // The commit phase of the speculative execution.
    // It checks if the reservation was successful and finalizes the match.
    // Returns true if the commit succeeded.
    // Returns false if the commit failed, indicating that speculative_for should retry.
    bool commit(edgeId i) {
        vertexId u = E[i].u;
        vertexId v = E[i].v;

        // Check if we won the reservation for both endpoints.
        // Acquire semantics ensure we see the writes from other threads that might have won.
        bool u_won = (reservations[u].load(std::memory_order_acquire) == i);
        bool v_won = (reservations[v].load(std::memory_order_acquire) == i);

        if (u_won && v_won) {
            // Success! This edge is in the matching. The reservation is now permanent.
            return true;
        } else {
            // Failure. We didn't win both. We must release any vertex we did win
            // so that other edges can claim it.
            constexpr vertexId unmatch_val = UNMATCHED;
            if (u_won) {
                // Use CAS to avoid overwriting a reservation from another edge in a subsequent round.
                // Release semantics to make the reset visible to other threads.
                reservations[u].compare_exchange_strong(i, unmatch_val, std::memory_order_release, std::memory_order_relaxed);
            }
            if (v_won) {
                reservations[v].compare_exchange_strong(i, unmatch_val, std::memory_order_release, std::memory_order_relaxed);
            }

            // Commit failed. speculative_for will retry this edge. The `reserve`
            // check will eventually stop retrying if it becomes permanently blocked.
            return false;
        }
    }
};

// Computes a maximal matching in parallel.
parlay::sequence<edgeId> maximalMatching(edges const &EA) {
    size_t n = max(EA.numCols, EA.numRows);
    size_t m = EA.nonZeros;

    if (m == 0) {
        return parlay::sequence<edgeId>();
    }

    // `reservations[v]` stores the ID of the edge that has reserved/matched vertex `v`.
    // Initialized to UNMATCHED.
    constexpr vertexId UNMATCHED = std::numeric_limits<vertexId>::max();
    auto reservations = parlay::sequence<std::atomic<vertexId>>(n);
    parlay::parallel_for(0, n, [&](size_t i) {
        reservations[i].store(UNMATCHED, std::memory_order_relaxed);
    });

    // Create the step object for the speculative loop.
    MatchingStep step(EA, reservations);

    // Run the reservation-based algorithm in parallel over all edges.
    // The granularity parameter (20) is a reasonable default.
    // `hasState=false` means we use a single step object for all threads.
    pbbs::speculative_for(step, (edgeId)0, (edgeId)m, 20, false);

    // Collect the results.
    // An edge `i = (u, v)` is in the matching if it successfully reserved both `u` and `v`.
    // This means reservations[u] == i and reservations[v] == i. We only need to check one endpoint.
    auto matching_indices = parlay::filter(parlay::iota<edgeId>(m), [&](edgeId i) {
        // The speculative_for loop acts as a synchronizing point, so a relaxed
        // load would likely be sufficient. Using acquire for safety.
        return reservations[EA[i].u].load(std::memory_order_acquire) == i;
    });

    return matching_indices;
}
