An expert C++ programmer would recognize that the baseline implementation uses a deterministic priority scheme based on vertex IDs. While simple and correct, this can lead to poor performance on graphs with regular structures, such as the 3D grid graph specified in the problem description. In such cases, long dependency chains can form, effectively sequentializing the execution.

The fastest parallel MIS algorithms typically use randomization to break these symmetries and dependencies, ensuring rapid convergence in a logarithmic number of rounds with high probability. The proposed solution replaces the deterministic, speculative approach with a more standard and robust bulk-synchronous parallel (BSP) algorithm based on random priorities.

### Key Improvements:

1.  **Randomized Priorities**: Instead of using vertex IDs for priority, we assign each vertex a pseudo-random priority by hashing its ID. This is a standard technique that is deterministic, requires no synchronization to compute, and is highly effective at breaking symmetries, leading to much better performance on structured graphs like grids and preventing worst-case scenarios on general graphs.

2.  **Explicit Frontier-Based Execution**: The algorithm operates in rounds on a frontier of "active" (undecided) vertices. In each round, it identifies a set of new vertices to add to the MIS, removes them and their neighbors from the active set, and repeats until no active vertices remain. This explicit, round-based structure is a common pattern in high-performance parallel graph algorithms and is implemented efficiently using ParlayLib's `pack` and `parallel_for` primitives.

3.  **Correct and Efficient Parallel Updates**: The state of each vertex (`flags` array) is updated in parallel. Adding vertices to the MIS and deactivating their neighbors requires care to avoid race conditions. The solution uses a two-pass update within each round and a GCC/Clang atomic built-in (`__atomic_compare_exchange_n`) for conflict-free updates, which is highly efficient on modern hardware.

This revised algorithm is not only correct but is also expected to be significantly faster and more scalable than the baseline, especially for the specified grid graph inputs.

```cpp
#start
#include <iostream>
#include "parlay/parallel.h"
#include "parlay/primitives.h"
#include "parlay/hash.h"
#include "common/graph.h"
#include "MIS.h"

// **************************************************************
//    MAXIMAL INDEPENDENT SET
// **************************************************************

parlay::sequence<char> maximalIndependentSet(Graph const &G) {
  size_t n = G.n;
  if (n == 0) {
    return parlay::sequence<char>();
  }

  // Flags: 0 for undecided, 1 for in the MIS, 2 for a neighbor is in the MIS.
  auto flags = parlay::sequence<char>::uninitialized(n);
  parlay::parallel_for(0, n, [&](size_t i) {
    flags[i] = 0;
  });

  // Assign a pseudo-random priority to each vertex to break symmetries.
  // Using a hash of the vertex ID is deterministic and efficient.
  // This is critical for performance on graphs with regular structure (e.g., grids),
  // where using vertex IDs as priorities leads to sequential dependency chains.
  auto priorities = parlay::sequence<uint64_t>::uninitialized(n);
  parlay::parallel_for(0, n, [&](size_t i) {
    priorities[i] = parlay::hash64(i);
  });

  // The frontier of active (undecided) vertices.
  auto active = parlay::iota<vertexId>(n);

  while (active.size() > 0) {
    // 1. Select candidates for the MIS.
    // An active vertex is a candidate if it has a higher priority than all its
    // active neighbors.
    auto is_candidate = parlay::sequence<bool>::uninitialized(active.size());
    parlay::parallel_for(0, active.size(), [&](size_t i) {
      vertexId u = active[i];
      uint64_t u_prio = priorities[u];
      auto neighbors = G[u];
      bool is_max = true;
      for (vertexId j = 0; j < neighbors.degree; j++) {
        vertexId v = neighbors.Neighbors[j];
        // Consider only active neighbors (flags[v] == 0).
        if (flags[v] == 0) {
          uint64_t v_prio = priorities[v];
          // Break ties with vertex ID to ensure a total ordering.
          if (v_prio > u_prio || (v_prio == u_prio && v > u)) {
            is_max = false;
            break;
          }
        }
      }
      is_candidate[i] = is_max;
    });

    // 2. Add candidates to the MIS and mark their neighbors.
    // This is done in two passes over the candidates to avoid race conditions.
    // First pass: mark the candidates themselves as being in the MIS.
    parlay::parallel_for(0, active.size(), [&](size_t i) {
      if (is_candidate[i]) {
        vertexId u = active[i];
        flags[u] = 1;
      }
    });

    // Second pass: mark the neighbors of the new MIS vertices.
    parlay::parallel_for(0, active.size(), [&](size_t i) {
      if (is_candidate[i]) {
        vertexId u = active[i];
        auto neighbors = G[u];
        for (vertexId j = 0; j < neighbors.degree; j++) {
          vertexId v = neighbors.Neighbors[j];
          // Atomically mark undecided neighbors (flags == 0) as removed (flags = 2).
          // This prevents race conditions where multiple new MIS vertices
          // are neighbors of the same vertex v.
          char expected = 0;
          __atomic_compare_exchange_n(&flags[v], &expected, (char)2, 
                                      false, __ATOMIC_RELAXED, __ATOMIC_RELAXED);
        }
      }
    });

    // 3. Update the active set by removing vertices that are now decided
    // (either in MIS or a neighbor is).
    auto still_active_map = parlay::delayed_seq<bool>(active.size(), [&](size_t i) {
      return flags[active[i]] == 0;
    });
    active = parlay::pack(active, still_active_map);
  }

  return flags;
}
