An expert implementation of parallel Maximal Independent Set (MIS) should be both correct and highly performant. The provided baseline uses a `speculative_for` loop with vertex IDs for priority. While correct, this approach has two main performance limitations:
1.  **ID-based Priority**: Using vertex IDs for priority can lead to poor parallelism on certain graph structures (e.g., paths or graphs with low-ID hubs), effectively serializing parts of the computation.
2.  **Execution Model**: The general-purpose `speculative_for` may introduce overhead compared to a specialized, round-based implementation tailored for MIS.

To create a faster implementation, I will use a well-established, highly parallel algorithm for MIS, often attributed to Luby or Blelloch. This algorithm is randomized and operates in rounds on a diminishing set of active vertices.

### Algorithm Description

1.  **Initialization**:
    *   All vertices are initially marked as `undecided` (active).
    *   A random permutation is generated to assign a unique, random priority to each vertex. This is a one-time setup cost and is crucial for breaking symmetries and ensuring high parallelism across various graph structures.

2.  **Iterative Rounds**: The algorithm proceeds in rounds until no vertices are undecided. In each round:
    *   **Candidate Selection**: In parallel, each active vertex inspects its neighbors. A vertex selects itself as a candidate for the MIS if it has a higher priority than all of its *active* neighbors.
    *   **Update MIS**: All candidate vertices are added to the MIS. Since the selection criteria ensure no two adjacent vertices can be candidates in the same round, these updates are conflict-free.
    *   **Remove Neighbors**: All neighbors of the newly added MIS vertices are removed from consideration for future rounds.
    *   **Filter Active Set**: The set of active vertices is compacted for the next round by removing all vertices that have been decided (either added to the MIS or removed as a neighbor).

### Performance Advantages

*   **Randomized Priorities**: The random permutation ensures that, with high probability, a constant fraction of active vertices are resolved in each round, leading to an expected `O(log n)` rounds for convergence. This avoids the worst-case scenarios of deterministic priority schemes.
*   **Active Set Management**: By explicitly managing and filtering the set of active vertices, the algorithm focuses computational work only where needed. The work per round decreases as the MIS is constructed, which is much more efficient than iterating over all `n` vertices in every round.
*   **High Parallelism**: All steps within a round (candidate selection, updates, filtering) are highly parallel and can be implemented efficiently using ParlayLib's primitives like `parallel_for` and `filter`.

The following C++ code implements this high-performance parallel MIS algorithm.

#start
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include "parlay/parallel.h"
#include "parlay/primitives.h"
#include "parlay/random.h"
#include "common/graph.h"
#include <atomic>

// This implementation uses a variant of Luby's algorithm, also known as
// Blelloch's randomized algorithm. It proceeds in rounds. In each round,
// it processes the set of "active" (undecided) vertices.
//
// 1. Priority Assignment:
//    A random, unique priority is assigned to every vertex at the beginning
//    using a random permutation. This is done only once. A lower permutation
//    value implies a higher priority. This avoids the pitfalls of using vertex
//    IDs for priorities, which can lead to near-sequential execution on certain
//    graph structures (e.g., line graphs).
//
// 2. Candidate Selection:
//    In each round, an active vertex `u` is selected as a candidate to join the
//    MIS if it has a higher priority than all of its currently active neighbors.
//    Because priorities are unique, no two adjacent vertices can be selected in
//    the same round, eliminating the need for complex conflict resolution.
//
// 3. MIS Update:
//    All candidate vertices are added to the MIS. Their `Flag` is set to 1.
//
// 4. Neighbor Removal:
//    All neighbors of the newly added MIS vertices are removed from the active set
//    for future rounds. Their `Flag` is set to 2. An atomic compare-and-swap is
//    used to handle the case where a vertex is a neighbor of multiple new MIS
//    vertices.
//
// 5. Active Set Update:
//    The set of active vertices for the next round is generated by filtering out
//    all vertices that have been decided (either added to MIS or removed).
//
// This process repeats until no active vertices remain. The algorithm is highly
// parallel and is expected to terminate in O(log n) rounds with high probability.
// The use of an explicit active set (`active_vertices`) focuses computation on the
// remaining undecided vertices, which is more efficient than iterating over all
// n vertices in every round, especially in later stages.

parlay::sequence<char> maximalIndependentSet(Graph const &G) {
  size_t n = G.n;
  if (n == 0) {
    return parlay::sequence<char>();
  }

  // Flags:
  // 0: undecided (active)
  // 1: in the MIS
  // 2: neighbor of a vertex in the MIS (removed)
  auto Flags = parlay::sequence<char>(n, (char)0);

  // Use a random permutation to assign a unique priority to each vertex.
  // p[v] gives the priority of vertex v. Lower value means higher priority.
  // This is more robust than using vertex IDs for priority.
  parlay::random_generator<std::mt19937> rand_gen;
  parlay::sequence<vertexId> p = parlay::random_permutation(n, rand_gen);

  // The set of vertices that are still undecided.
  auto active_vertices = parlay::iota<vertexId>(n);
  size_t num_active = n;

  while (num_active > 0) {
    // 1. Select candidates to join the MIS.
    // A vertex is a candidate if it has higher priority than all its active neighbors.
    auto is_candidate = parlay::sequence<bool>(num_active);
    parlay::parallel_for(0, num_active, [&](size_t i) {
      vertexId u = active_vertices[i];
      auto u_neighbors = G[u];
      bool highest_priority = true;
      for (size_t j = 0; j < u_neighbors.degree; ++j) {
        vertexId v = u_neighbors.Neighbors[j];
        // Check only active neighbors.
        if (Flags[v] == 0) {
          // A neighbor with a lower permutation value has higher priority.
          if (p[v] < p[u]) {
            highest_priority = false;
            break;
          }
        }
      }
      is_candidate[i] = highest_priority;
    });

    // 2. Add candidates to the MIS.
    // This is done in a separate loop to create a synchronization point,
    // ensuring all reads for candidate selection are from the same state.
    parlay::parallel_for(0, num_active, [&](size_t i) {
      if (is_candidate[i]) {
        vertexId u = active_vertices[i];
        // Since no two adjacent vertices can both be candidates, this write is safe.
        Flags[u] = 1;
      }
    });

    // 3. Remove neighbors of the new MIS vertices.
    parlay::parallel_for(0, num_active, [&](size_t i) {
      if (is_candidate[i]) {
        vertexId u = active_vertices[i];
        auto u_neighbors = G[u];
        for (size_t j = 0; j < u_neighbors.degree; ++j) {
          vertexId v = u_neighbors.Neighbors[j];
          // Atomically mark undecided neighbors as removed.
          // This handles the case where a vertex is a neighbor of multiple
          // new MIS vertices concurrently.
          char undecided_state = 0;
          parlay::compare_and_swap(&Flags[v], undecided_state, (char)2);
        }
      }
    });

    // 4. Update the active set for the next round.
    active_vertices = parlay::filter(active_vertices, [&](const vertexId& u) {
      return Flags[u] == 0;
    });
    num_active = active_vertices.size();
  }

  return Flags;
}
