An expert C++ programmer would recognize that the baseline implementation, while parallel, is not the most efficient. It iterates over all vertices in every round of its speculative execution, even those that have already been decided. Additionally, using vertex IDs for priority can lead to poor performance on certain graph structures.

A faster and more standard approach for parallel MIS is a variant of Luby's algorithm. This algorithm proceeds in rounds, rapidly shrinking the set of vertices that need to be considered. Here's a summary of the improved algorithm:

1.  **Initialization**:
    *   An array `Flags` of size `n` tracks the state of each vertex: `0` (undecided), `1` (in the MIS), or `2` (neighbor of a vertex in the MIS).
    *   A sequence `Active` holds the indices of all currently undecided vertices. Initially, this is all vertices `0..n-1`.
    *   A unique random 64-bit priority is assigned to each vertex to break ties symmetrically and efficiently.

2.  **Rounds**: The algorithm iterates as long as there are active vertices. In each round:
    *   **Candidate Selection**: In parallel, each active vertex `u` checks its active neighbors. If `u` has a higher priority than all of its active neighbors, it becomes a candidate for the MIS. This selection process guarantees that the set of all candidates is an independent set.
    *   **Update MIS**: All candidate vertices are added to the MIS by setting their `Flags` to `1`. Since candidates form an independent set, this step is embarrassingly parallel.
    *   **Update Neighbors**: In parallel, for each new vertex `u` added to the MIS, all of its neighbors `v` are marked as removed (`Flags[v] = 2`). A compare-and-swap operation is used here to safely handle cases where a vertex is a neighbor of multiple new MIS members.
    *   **Update Active Set**: The `Active` set is filtered to remove all vertices that are no longer undecided (i.e., their `Flags` are now `1` or `2`). This `pack` operation is highly efficient.

This round-based approach with an explicit active set is work-efficient. The size of the active set decreases significantly in each round (provably by a constant fraction in expectation), leading to `O(log n)` rounds and total work proportional to the number of vertices and edges. This is a significant improvement over the baseline, which performs `O(n)` work in every speculative attempt.

Here is the high-performance C++ implementation:

#start
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include "parlay/parallel.h"
#include "parlay/primitives.h"
#include "parlay/random.h"
#include "parlay/atomics.h"
#include "common/graph.h"
#include "MIS.h"

// **************************************************************
//    MAXIMAL INDEPENDENT SET
// **************************************************************

// A parallel implementation of Luby's algorithm for Maximal Independent Set.
//
// The algorithm proceeds in rounds. In each round, it processes the set of
// 'active' vertices (those not yet in the MIS and not adjacent to any vertex
// in the MIS).
//
// 1. Assign a unique random priority to each vertex.
//
// 2. In each round:
//    a. Select a set of candidate vertices to add to the MIS. A vertex is a
//       candidate if it is active and has a higher priority than all of its
//       active neighbors. The set of candidates is guaranteed to be an
//       independent set.
//    b. Add all candidate vertices to the MIS.
//    c. Remove the candidates and all their neighbors from the active set.
//
// 3. Repeat until the active set is empty.
//
// This implementation uses an explicit 'Active' set, which is filtered in
// each round. This is generally more efficient than iterating over all n
// vertices, especially in later rounds when the number of active vertices
// is small.
parlay::sequence<char> maximalIndependentSet(Graph const &G) {
  size_t n = G.n;

  if (n == 0) {
    return parlay::sequence<char>();
  }

  // Flags: 0 = undecided, 1 = in MIS, 2 = neighbor of MIS vertex
  auto Flags = parlay::sequence<char>(n, 0);

  // Active set, initially all vertices
  auto Active = parlay::tabulate(n, [&](size_t i) { return static_cast<vertexId>(i); });
  size_t num_active = n;

  // Generate unique random priorities for tie-breaking.
  // A 64-bit priority is formed by combining a random number and the vertex ID.
  parlay::random_generator<std::mt19937> gen;
  auto Priorities = parlay::tabulate(n, [&](size_t i) {
    auto r = gen[i];
    return (static_cast<uint64_t>(r.rand()) << 32) | i;
  });

  while (num_active > 0) {
    // 1. Select Candidates
    // A vertex is a candidate if its priority is a local maximum among its
    // active neighbors.
    auto is_candidate = parlay::sequence<bool>(num_active);
    parlay::parallel_for(0, num_active, [&](size_t i) {
      vertexId u = Active[i];
      bool u_is_candidate = true;
      auto neighbors = G[u];
      for (size_t j = 0; j < neighbors.degree; j++) {
        vertexId v = neighbors.Neighbors[j];
        // Check only active neighbors (Flags[v] == 0).
        // If a neighbor has higher priority, u is not a candidate.
        if (Flags[v] == 0 && Priorities[v] > Priorities[u]) {
          u_is_candidate = false;
          break;
        }
      }
      is_candidate[i] = u_is_candidate;
    });

    // 2. Add candidates to the MIS and mark their neighbors.
    // This is done in two steps to avoid race conditions.
    // First, add candidates to MIS. Since the candidate set is an independent
    // set, this can be done with simple writes without atomics.
    parlay::parallel_for(0, num_active, [&](size_t i) {
      if (is_candidate[i]) {
        Flags[Active[i]] = 1;
      }
    });

    // Second, mark neighbors of the new MIS vertices.
    parlay::parallel_for(0, num_active, [&](size_t i) {
      if (is_candidate[i]) {
        vertexId u = Active[i];
        auto neighbors = G[u];
        for (size_t j = 0; j < neighbors.degree; j++) {
          vertexId v = neighbors.Neighbors[j];
          // Mark undecided neighbors as 'removed'.
          // Use CAS to handle the case where multiple new MIS vertices
          // share a neighbor. A simple write would be a race.
          char expected = 0;
          parlay::compare_and_swap(&Flags[v], expected, (char)2);
        }
      }
    });

    // 3. Update the active set by filtering out vertices that are no longer undecided.
    auto still_active_flags = parlay::tabulate(num_active, [&](size_t i) {
      return Flags[Active[i]] == 0;
    });

    Active = parlay::pack(Active, still_active_flags);
    num_active = Active.size();
  }

  return Flags;
}
