3.  **Guaranteed Progress**: In each round, the priority-based algorithm is guaranteed to add at least one vertex to the MIS from each connected component of the remaining graph, ensuring the algorithm terminates quickly (typically in a logarithmic number of rounds). The baseline offers no such guarantee and can perform poorly on certain graph structures.
4.  **Scalable Parallelism**: The core operations—calculating local maxima, updating vertex states, and filtering the active vertex set—are all implemented using highly-optimized, data-parallel primitives from ParlayLib (`parallel_for`, `tabulate`, `pack`, `filter`). This structure scales well with the number of processor cores.

The resulting code is not only more performant and scalable but also conceptually simpler and easier to reason about in a parallel context.

